{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01UJY8TsiRSCBfuLCMjNGmRD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior and determine the minimum test level needed to catch a real failure.\n\n**Key considerations:**\n- Unit: Single function/object, no I/O, fully deterministic\n- Integration: Multiple modules wired together, may use local DB/filesystem\n- System: Subprocess, OS behavior, real HTTP, real external API\n- Agentic: Real LLM/AI/ML model with non-determinism\n- Workflow: Multiple agentic steps in sequence\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n### 1. A cell containing `=SUM(A1:A10)` evaluates to the correct sum\n- This is a single formula evaluation\n- No external dependencies, no I/O, no LLM\n- Could be tested with: create a spreadsheet object, set cells A1:A10, evaluate formula\n- A pure mock of cell lookup would work fine here\n- Real failure modes: incorrect range parsing, wrong accumulation logic, type coercion issues\n- **Level: Unit** — The formula engine's SUM function and range resolution are local functions. You can test by:\n  1. Creating cells with known values\n  2. Evaluating the formula\n  3. Checking the result\n- All logic is in-process, no I/O needed\n- Confidence: Unit ~0.95, Integration ~0.05 (edge case: if range parsing depends on some config file, but unlikely)\n\n### 2. Cell referencing another cell with a formula (cascaded formulas)\n- Example: B1 = `=A1*2`, then C1 = `=B1+1`\n- Requires: cell lookup, formula parsing, recursive evaluation\n- No external I/O, fully deterministic\n- Real failure modes: incorrect order of evaluation, circular dependency not caught properly (wait, that's #3), incorrect value propagation\n- Could be tested with multiple cells in memory\n- **Level: Unit** — This is still in-process evaluation of multiple cells. You:\n  1. Create cells with formulas\n  2. Evaluate the dependent cell\n  3. Check it resolved correctly\n- The key is that all data is in-memory; you're just testing the evaluation logic\n- Confidence: Unit ~0.85, Integration ~0.15 (if there's some caching mechanism that requires multiple evaluation passes, might need integration-level setup)\n\n### 3. Circular dependency detection (A1→B1, B1→A1)\n- Requires: graph traversal, cycle detection\n- No I/O, fully deterministic\n- Real failure modes: infinite loop, missed cycle detection, incorrect error message\n- Could be tested with in-memory cells\n- **Level: Unit** — Pure graph algorithm testing with cells in memory to verify the cycle detection logic catches the loop and raises the appropriate error.\n- Confidence: Unit ~0.9, Integration ~0.1\n\n### 4. VLOOKUP with exact match and error handling\n- This is a built-in function implementation\n- Requires: table lookup, exact match logic, error handling\n- No I/O, fully deterministic\n- Real failure modes: case sensitivity, wrong column returned, incorrect error type\n- **Level: Unit** — Test the VLOOKUP function with a table (in-memory). Create test tables, evaluate VLOOKUP formulas, check results and errors.\n- Confidence: Unit ~0.9, Integration ~0.1\n\n### 5. IF with nested conditions\n- Pure formula evaluation logic\n- No I/O, fully deterministic\n- Real failure modes: incorrect condition evaluation, wrong branch taken, type coercion\n- **Level: Unit** — Test IF function with nested IFs. Create cells with complex IF form ulas, evaluate, check results.\n- Confidence: Unit ~0.9, Integration ~0.1\n\n### 6. CONCATENATE with separator and empty cell handling\n- Built-in function logic\n- No I/O, fully deterministic\n- Real failure modes: wrong separator, blank strings inserted, type coercion issues\n- **Level: Unit** — Test CONCATENATE function with various inputs including empty cells\n- Confidence: Unit ~0.9, Integration ~0.1\n\n### 7. Cross-sheet reference resolution\n- Example: `=Sheet2!A1+1`\n- Requires: sheet lookup, cell reference parsing, cross-sheet navigation\n- No I/O yet (still in-memory), but requires knowledge of multiple sheets\n- Real failure modes: wrong sheet selected, reference not resolved, sheet not found\n- **Level: Unit or Integration?** — Could be Unit if you have a workbook object with multiple sheets in memory, or Integration if it requires actual sheet management. The distinction depends on whether sheets are pre-loaded or need to be accessed dynamically.\n- Most likely: Unit — create a workbook with two sheets, set values, evaluate cross-sheet formula\n- Confidence: Unit ~0.75, Integration ~0.25\n\n### 8. Dependent formulas recalculate in correct topological order\n- This requires: a dependency graph, topological sort, recalculation logic\n- When you change A1, B1 (=A1+1) and C1 (=B1+2) must both recalculate in order\n- No I/O, fully deterministic\n- Real failure modes: incorrect recalculation order, stale values, exponential recalculation\n- **Level: Integration** — Why\n\n? Multiple cells need to be wired together and when one changes, all dependents must update in the correct sequence. Mocking cell lookups could hide caching or lazy evaluation bugs that cause stale values. The real boundary is verifying that changing a single cell triggers proper updates across the entire dependency chain.\n- Confidence: Unit ~0.2, Integration ~0.75, System ~0.05\n\n### 9. Undo operation restores formula and dependent values\n- Requires: undo/redo stack, formula storage, dependent value storage\n- No I/O (yet)\n\nFully deterministic with no external dependencies. Real failures occur when undo doesn't restore formulas, doesn't restore dependent values, or only partially undoes changes. This needs integration testing because you're verifying that a sequence of operations—setting formulas, triggering recalculation, making changes, undoing—correctly restores the entire workbook state. Mocking the undo stack would miss bugs where dependent values aren't properly stored or retrieved during restoration. The actual failure boundary is whether all side effects from multiple operations are reversed together.\n- Confidence: Unit ~0.15, Integration ~0.8, System ~0.05\n\n### 10. Workbook persistence and loading (save\n\n/load from disk)\n- Requires: binary file I/O, serialization/deserialization\n- **REAL-INFRA question**: Does this depend on the filesystem? YES → At least System.\n- Real failure modes: data corruption, precision loss in floats, formula not serialized, dependent values lost\n- **Level: System** — Why?\n  - This involves real file I/O (save to disk, load from disk)\n  - A mock file system might not catch all failures (file handle issues, disk space, permissions)\n  - The real failure boundary is: can you actually persist and reload the workbook?\n  - Realistic test: create workbook with formulas and data, save to file, load from file, verify identical\n- Confidence: System ~0.8, Integration ~0.15, Unit ~0.05\n\nLet me refine these:\n\n1. **SUM formula evaluation** → **Unit**\n   - Confidence: {Unit: 0.95, Integration: 0.04, System: 0.01, Agentic: 0.0, Workflow: 0.0}\n\n2. **Cascaded formula evaluation** → **Unit**\n   - Confidence: {Unit: 0.85, Integration: 0.12, System: 0.02, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.0}\n\n3. **Circular dependency detection** → **Unit**\n   - Confidence: {Unit: 0.90, Integration: 0.08, System: 0.01, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.0}\n\n4. **VLOOKUP exact match and error** → **Unit**\n   - Confidence: {Unit: 0.90, Integration: 0.08, System: 0.01, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.0}\n\n5. **Nested IF conditions** → **Unit**\n   - Confidence: {Unit: 0.90, Integration: 0.08, System: 0.01, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.0}\n\n6. **CONCATENATE with separator and empty cells** → **Unit**\n   - Confidence: {Unit: 0.88, Integration: 0.10, System: 0.01, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.0}\n\n7. **Cross-sheet reference resolution** → **Unit**\n   - Sheets are just cell collections in memory, so no I/O overhead during testing. Confidence: {Unit: 0.75, Integration: 0.20, System: 0.03, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n8. **Dependent formulas recalculate in topological order** → **Integration**\n   - This requires wiring multiple cells together and verifying the recalculation sequence follows the dependency graph correctly, which goes beyond testing a single function. Confidence: {Unit: 0.15, Integration: 0.80, System: 0.03, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n9. **Undo restores formula and dependent values** → **Integration**\n   - Requires: workbook state, undo stack, formula storage, dependent value storage. Need to verify the complete state is restored after undo. Confidence: {Unit: 0.10, Integration: 0.85, System: 0.03, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n10. **Workbook persistence (save/load)** → **System**\n    - Involves real filesystem I/O and requires verifying data integrity through serialization/deserialization cycles. Confidence: {Unit: 0.02, Integration: 0.13, System: 0.83, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01}\n\nActually, reconsidering #8 and #9—could these be Unit level? For #8, the test is creating cells with dependencies, changing one, and verifying dependents recalculate in the right order. This isolates the recalculation algorithm itself. For #9, I'm testing whether the undo mechanism correctly restores state, but I need to think about whether that's really just testing the algorithm in isolation or if it requires the full system integration.\n\nThe key question: what's the minimum level needed to catch real failures? If A1 changes and B1 recalculates based on the old value instead of the new one, that's a real failure. I could catch this at Unit level by testing the recalculation logic directly with in-memory objects, but the test would need to exercise cell change detection, dependency tracking, and topological sorting—multiple components working together. That pushes it toward Integration. Similarly, undo requires multiple cells and their state interactions, making it harder to isolate as a pure Unit test.\n\nRefining the boundaries: Unit tests focus on single functions or algorithms in isolation (evaluating a SUM formula, detecting circular dependencies). Integration tests wire together multiple modules like the formula engine and storage layer (cells depending on each other, undo across the system). System tests involve actual I/O or OS calls (saving and loading files).\n\nReconsidering the classifications: SUM, cascaded formulas, circular dependency detection, VLOOKUP, IF, and CONCATENATE are all Unit tests since they're individual formula evaluations. Cross-sheet references stay Unit if sheets are just in-memory collections. Topological recalculation becomes Integration because it coordinates multiple cells through a dependency graph. Undo is Integration since it involves the formula engine, undo stack, and storage working together. Save/load is System due to real file I/O.\n\nNow I need to think more carefully about cascaded formulas and cross-sheet references—whether they truly stay within Unit boundaries or if they cross module lines that would make them Integration.\n\nFor cascaded formulas like B1 = A1*2 and C1 = B1+1, the test would set up multiple cells and evaluate C1 to check the result. The formula engine handles the recursion internally, so it's still a single module being tested. No mocking needed—just testing the evaluation logic itself.\n\nFor cross-sheet references like Sheet2!A1 + 1, the test creates a workbook with multiple sheets, sets a value in one sheet, and evaluates a formula in another. This requires coordinating across sheets, which suggests Integration testing since you're testing how the formula engine interacts with the sheet collection.\n\nActually, stepping back—I'm overcomplicating the boundaries here. The real question is whether the failure happens within a single process or crosses external boundaries. All of these scenarios—SUM, cascaded formulas, circular references, VLOOKUP, IF, CONCATENATE, and cross-sheet references—are handled entirely in-process by the formula engine. Sheet resolution is just part of the cell reference lookup mechanism. These are all Unit tests because they test the formula evaluation logic without crossing into external systems or modules.\n\nBut topological recalculation is different. It requires setting up a dependency graph, changing a cell value, and verifying that all dependent cells update in the correct sequence. This crosses multiple internal boundaries—cell change detection, dependency tracking, and the recalculation engine itself. That's Integration.\n\nSimilarly, undo operations need to set up state, trigger an undo action, and verify complete restoration across the formula engine, undo stack, and storage. That's also Integration because it spans multiple modules.\n\nSave and load operations involve actual file I/O, making them System tests.\n\nFor cascaded formulas specifically, I could mock the cell lookup to isolate just the formula evaluation logic, but doing so would hide potential bugs in how cells actually resolve their dependencies. The test is more valuable when it exercises the real cell lookup mechanism.\n\nMy final categorization:\n1-7: Unit\n8-9: Integration\n10: System\n\nFor confidence, I'm assessing how likely each minimum level is correct and whether a lower level could suffice. SUM logic is self-contained with no external dependencies, so Unit testing is appropriate with high confidence. The integration tests require cross-module verification that can't be achieved at the unit level. there's a small chance sheet existence or loading would need Integration testing.\n\nFor topological recalculation, the key issue is whether all dependent cells update correctly when one changes—that's an Integration concern since it involves multiple cells with interdependencies. Unit testing alone wouldn't capture the full recalculation flow across the spreadsheet.\n\nUndo functionality similarly requires Integration testing because it involves multiple operations and state restoration across the system.\n\nSave and load operations demand System testing since they depend on actual file I/O—mocking the filesystem wouldn't catch real failures in how data persists and reloads.\n\nReconsidering topological recalculation and undo: the critical failure mode for recalculation is whether changing one cell propagates correctly through its dependents, which requires testing the actual cell lookup and dependency chain rather than mocking individual components. To catch this with a unit test, I'd need to isolate the recalculation logic and test it directly—but that test would still require setting up multiple cells and verifying propagation, which blurs the line into integration territory. With mocks, I could test just the algorithm, but that wouldn't verify the actual wiring between cells works correctly.\n\nThe real issue is that this failure only manifests when cells are connected and changes flow through them in sequence. So integration testing makes more sense—I'm verifying the cells are properly linked and updates cascade in the right order. A unit test would only catch bugs in the recalculation algorithm itself, not in how cells depend on each other.\n\nThat said, if the recalculation engine is a single, self-contained component, I could argue for unit testing it in isolation.\n\nNow for #9 with undo: a real failure would be when undoing a change doesn't restore a dependent formula's value correctly. To test this at the unit level, I'd mock the undo stack and verify it gets called—but that doesn't actually confirm undo restores the right state. At the integration level, I'd create cells, make changes, trigger undo, and check the state is correct. That's the realistic scenario and would catch actual failures.\n\nI'm confident #9 is integration. For #8, I'm settling on integration too, since the real failure boundary is when multiple cells update together.\n\nLet me revisit #2 one more time. With cascaded formulas like B1 = A1*2 and C1 = B1+1, setting A1 = 5 should make C1 evaluate to 11. A mocked cell lookup would return 5 for A1 and 10 for B1, and the formula engine would correctly evaluate B1 as a formula and use that result in C1. That's unit-level testing of the formula engine itself.\n\nBut the real bug could be: when evaluating C1 = B1+1, the system retrieves B1's stored value (maybe still 0) instead of its current calculated value (10). This is a caching or state-freshness issue that only shows up when formulas depend on other formulas.\n\nTo catch this, I'd need to actually evaluate B1 and confirm it returns the current value, not a stale one. This starts looking like integration territory since it involves formula interdependencies and state consistency.\n\nActually, the formula engine should always re-evaluate formulas when referenced. If B1 is a formula, it gets evaluated on demand in C1. That's all in-process logic, so it stays unit-level.\n\nMy final breakdown: #1-7 are unit tests, #8-9 are integration, and #10 is system-level. value, which is the actual test of the formula engine's behavior.\n\nI'm confident #2 is unit-level. Though I should think about whether cascaded formulas might actually cross component boundaries. If the formula engine and cell lookup are separate components, then evaluating B1 (which itself contains a formula) would involve the engine calling into the lookup component, which returns another formula that needs evaluation. That would make it integration-level. But if the formula engine is monolithic and handles all of that internally—formula parsing, cell references, recursive evaluation—then it stays unit-level. The distinction really hinges on the actual architecture.\n\nGiven the problem doesn't specify, I'll treat the formula engine as the primary component being tested. Cascaded formulas are just a more complex input to that component, not a cross-component interaction. So unit-level seems right, though I could see integration being defensible depending on how the system is structured.\n\nThe real question is whether a mock would catch this. If I mock cell lookups to return fixed values, I'd miss cases where a formula references another formula that hasn't been evaluated yet. But if I set up actual cell objects with formulas and evaluate them in-process, the engine handles the cascading logic internally—that's still unit testing. The test would create cells A1 (value 5), B1 (formula =A1*2), C1 (formula =B1+1), then verify C1 evaluates to 11. This requires the engine to recursively evaluate B1 when computing C1, but it's all happening within a single component. I'll stick with Unit (0.80, 0.17, 0.01, 0.01, 0.01) for cascaded formulas.\n\nFor topological recalculation, the distinction is clearer. A unit test could mock cells and verify the algorithm orders them correctly, but the real failure mode is when actual cells in a workbook don't trigger updates in the right sequence. That requires multiple cells wired together in the actual system. Similarly, undo needs to verify that editing a formula, undoing it, and checking both the formula text and dependent cell values all work together—that's an integration concern because you're testing the coordination between the undo system and the cell update system.\n\nFor cross-sheet references, I need to think about whether sheet resolution is part of the formula engine itself or a separate component. If the formula engine handles sheet lookups internally, then creating actual sheet objects and evaluating the formula is still unit-level testing. The mock-miss would only apply if sheet resolution were a separate service being called.\n\nI'll classify #7 as Unit with meaningful probability for Integration, since sheet management could involve complexity like lazy loading or existence validation that might warrant integration testing.\n\nNow reconsidering #8 - the topological recalculation where changing A1 triggers B1 and C1 to recalculate in the right order. This feels like it needs actual dependency tracking and ordering logic working together, which suggests Integration level testing would be more appropriate than just testing the algorithm in isolation. ates to the correct sum of values in cells A1 through A10.\n   - Justification: This tests the SUM function's range parsing and accumulation logic. The test creates cells with known values, evaluates the formula, and verifies the result. All logic is in-process and deterministic; no I/O or external dependencies.\n   - Test description: Create cells A1 through A10 with specific numeric values, create a cell containing =SUM(A1:A10), evaluate it, and assert the result equals the expected sum.\n   - Minimum level: Unit\n   - Plan consistent: Yes (this is pure formula evaluation logic)\n   - Level probabilities: {Unit: 0.92, Integration: 0.06, System: 0.01, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.0}\n\n2. **Cascaded formula evaluation**\n   - Description: A cell referencing another cell that itself contains a formula correctly evaluates through the dependency chain.\n   - Justification: This requires the system to resolve multiple levels of formula dependencies and ensure values propagate correctly through the chain. While still in-process, it tests the dependency resolution mechanism beyond a single formula.\n   - Test description: Set up cells where A1 contains a value, B1 contains =A1*2, and C1 contains =B1+5. Evaluate C1 and verify it produces the correct result based on the full chain.\n   - Minimum level: Unit\n   - Plan consistent: Yes (formula evaluation with dependency tracking, no external state)\n   - Level probabilities: {Unit: 0.85, Integration: 0.10, System: 0.03, Agentic: 0.01, Workflow: 0.01}\n\n3. **Circular dependency detection**\n   - Description: When formulas reference each other in a cycle, the engine identifies this and returns an error rather than entering infinite recursion.\n   - Justification: Tests the cycle detection algorithm that prevents infinite loops during formula evaluation. This is a graph