{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01UJY8TsiRSCBfuLCMjNGmRD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01UvZR3n6to6BKw91uLvUErf","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A cell containing =SUM(A1:A10) evaluates to the correct sum of values in cells A1 through A10.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This tests the SUM function's range parsing and accumulation logic. The test creates cells with known values, evaluates the formula, and verifies the result. All logic is in-process and deterministic; no I/O or external dependencies. A mock cell lookup would correctly represent this behavior.","test_description":"Create cells A1 through A10 with specific numeric values (e.g., 1, 2, 3, ..., 10), create a cell containing =SUM(A1:A10), evaluate it, and assert the result equals 55.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.92,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A cell referencing another cell that contains a formula (e.g., =B1+1 where B1 is =A1*2) produces the correct cascaded result.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Tests recursive formula evaluation within the formula engine. The engine must correctly identify when a referenced cell contains a formula, evaluate that formula, and use the result. This is in-process logic. While it involves multiple cells, each is evaluated by the same formula engine component.","test_description":"Create cell A1 with value 5, cell B1 with formula =A1*2, cell C1 with formula =B1+1, evaluate C1, and assert it equals 11. Verify that B1's computed value (not a literal) is used in C1's evaluation.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The engine detects a circular dependency (A1 references B1, B1 references A1) and returns a circular reference error instead of looping.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Tests the cycle detection algorithm in the formula engine. This is a pure graph traversal algorithm that runs in-process with no I/O. Real failures (infinite recursion or undetected cycles) are both caught at Unit level when the algorithm is tested with circular references.","test_description":"Create cell A1 with formula =B1+1 and cell B1 with formula =A1+1, attempt to evaluate either cell, and assert a circular reference error is returned (not infinite recursion).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"VLOOKUP with an exact match returns the correct value from the lookup table, and returns an error when the key is not found.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Tests the VLOOKUP function implementation. This is a built-in function performing table lookup and exact matching. All logic is in-process and deterministic; no I/O or external dependencies. Failures in matching logic or error handling are caught at Unit level.","test_description":"Create a lookup table with key-value pairs. Test VLOOKUP(key, table, column) for an existing key and assert the correct value is returned. Test with a non-existent key and assert an appropriate error is returned.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The IF function correctly handles nested conditions (e.g., =IF(A1>10, IF(A1>20, \"high\", \"medium\"), \"low\")).","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Tests the IF function implementation with nested conditions. This is function evaluation logic; all operations are in-process and deterministic. Failures in condition evaluation or branch selection are caught at Unit level.","test_description":"Create cells with numeric values and test nested IF formulas (A1=5, expect 'low'; A1=15, expect 'medium'; A1=25, expect 'high'). Verify each branch is correctly taken for the corresponding input.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"CONCATENATE joins cell values with the correct separator and handles empty cells by skipping them rather than inserting blank strings.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Tests the CONCATENATE function implementation. This is built-in function logic; all operations are in-process and deterministic. Failures in string joining, empty cell handling, or separator logic are caught at Unit level.","test_description":"Create cells with values (e.g., 'A', '', 'B', 3, '') and test CONCATENATE with a separator (','), asserting the result is 'A,B,3' (empty cells skipped, values joined correctly).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"A formula referencing a cell in a different sheet (e.g., =Sheet2!A1+1) resolves correctly when the referenced sheet exists.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Tests sheet resolution within the formula engine. The engine parses the sheet reference, locates the sheet, looks up the cell, and uses its value. This is in-process logic. However, sheet resolution could involve lazy loading or existence checks that might require Integration.","test_description":"Create a workbook with two sheets. Set a value in Sheet2!A1. Create a formula in Sheet1 that references =Sheet2!A1+1, evaluate it, and assert the correct result. Test non-existent sheet reference and assert an appropriate error.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"When a referenced cell's value changes, all dependent formulas are recalculated in the correct topological order.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Tests dependency tracking and recalculation propagation. A real failure is: changing A1 causes B1 to recalculate with the old A1 value, or C1 recalculates before B1. MOCK-MISS: mocking cells would miss bugs where the actual dependency graph doesn't trigger recalculation correctly. This requires multiple cells wired together in a real workbook to verify topological ordering is correct. This crosses multiple components (dependency tracking, recalculation ordering, change detection).","test_description":"Create cells: A1=5, B1=A1*2 (expect 10), C1=B1+1 (expect 11). Change A1 to 10. Verify B1 recalculates to 20 and C1 recalculates to 21. Instrument the recalculation to verify B1 was recalculated before C1 (topological order).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"The undo operation after editing a formula restores both the formula text and all previously computed dependent values.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Tests the undo mechanism's state restoration completeness. A real failure is: undo restores the formula but not dependent values, or vice versa. MOCK-MISS: mocking the undo stack would only verify it's called, not that the state is actually restored. This requires a full workbook with multiple cells, formulas, and dependencies to verify all state is correctly preserved and restored. This crosses multiple components (formula engine, undo stack, storage).","test_description":"Create cells with dependencies (A1=5, B1=A1*2). Edit B1's formula (change to =A1*3), verify B1 updates to 15. Trigger undo and assert: the formula text reverts to =A1*2, B1 recomputes to 10, and any cells depending on B1 also revert to their prior values.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"Saving a workbook to disk and loading it back produces identical cell values and formulas — no data loss or precision change in floating-point results.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Tests file I/O serialization and deserialization. Real failures include data corruption, floating-point precision loss, formulas not serialized, or dependent values lost. REAL-INFRA: this depends on actual file system I/O. A mock file system might miss bugs in disk format, file handle management, or binary encoding. This is the real failure boundary: does the workbook survive a save/load cycle intact?","test_description":"Create a workbook with cells containing: formulas (=A1*2), numeric values (including floats like 3.14159), text, and dependencies. Serialize to a file on disk. Deserialize from that file. Assert all cell values match exactly (no precision loss), all formulas are identical, and all dependent cells recompute correctly after loading.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.84,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13520,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13520},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"73fcf831-886a-47d2-a25c-f03d704b7a34","uuid":"a81fc1cd-bbb0-4518-b2be-db61bfbb234c"}
